          "body": "The psalm opens with a completed act ('I have taken refuge,' v. 1) that grounds the petitions that follow. David does not arrive at God cautiously — he has already run to Him, and now asks that the run not prove shameful. The 'rock / fortress' imagery (vv. 2-3) is triple — tsur (craggy cliff), sela (bedrock), matsudah (stronghold) — piling up military and geological metaphors for a God who cannot be stormed. The petition in v. 3 anchors the expectation not in David's merit but in 'Your name's sake' — the LORD's own reputation is at stake in whether His refugee is delivered. This is not flattery; it is covenant logic. Verse 5 reaches the petition's climax: 'Into Your hand I commit my spirit.' The word 'commit' (*paqad*) in Hebrew carries the sense of entrusting a deposit for safekeeping — David places his entire self, his very *ruach*, into the custody of the God he has just named 'God of truth.' Jesus quotes this verse from the cross (Luke 23:46), and Stephen echoes it at his martyrdom (Acts 7:59), demonstrating that the verse is not only a prayer for preservation in physical danger but the language of ultimate self-surrender to the Father's will."
